What is Message queue?
    Message queuing allows applications to communicate by sending messages to each other. The
message queue provides a temporary message storage when the destination program is busy or not connected 
   So message queue is nothing but a queue it provides a temporary storage for the messages. The message queue is made up of producer, broker and consumer, where the producer will produce the message and it will send that message to the message broker and consumer will consume that message from the message broker. We can use a message queue for the asynchronous communication between
multiple applications 
   So here asynchronous communication meaning, consider the producer is sending message to the message broker then producers don't have to wait for the response, it can proceed with other remaining tasks. A producer can be a different application and consumer can be a different application and basically we use a message queue for asynchronous communication between multiple
applications

What is RabbitMQ ?
    Rabbit mq is nothing but a message queue that acts as a intermediary platform where different
applications can send and receive messages. It originally implements the advanced messaging queuing protocol(AMQP), but now rabbit MK also supports several other API protocols such as
STOMP, MQTT and HTTP. 

How RabbitMQ works
    Here producer basically produce the message and it will send that message to the exchange and then exchange will basically use that message along with some setup rules to you route that
message to the queue and then consumer will basically consume that message from the queue 
    So exchange and queue are the two components which are part of rabbitmq broker but
producer and consumer can be different applications, so producer is application that sends a message to the rabbitmq broker and consumer is the application that reads the message from
the rabbitmq broker 

Why use RabbitMQ in a Microservices
   Rabbit mq is one of the simplest freely available option for implementing messaging queues in your micro Services architecture. RabbitMQ is one of the popular messaging queue system that we can use in a micro services for our synchronous communication between multiple microservices 
   For example, we have three micro services like orderservice, stockservice and emailservice
and these microservices will communicate with each other using message broker, so message broker can be a rabbitmq or Apache Kappa or any other message queues 

RabbitMQ Core Concepts
1. Producer
      Producer is basically application that sends a messages, it does not send a messages directly to the consumer, it sends a message only to the rabbit mq broker w

2. Consumer 
    Consumer is application that reads and messages from the rabbitmq broker, there can be a multiple consumers that subscribe to the rabbitmq broker, for example there are three consumers have subscribed to the rabbitmq broker and whenever a producer will send a message to the rabbit mq broker then all these consumers will read that message from the rabbitmq broker 

3. Queue
      It is basically buffer or a storage in a rabbitmq broker to store the messages. So whenever producer sends a message to the rabbitmq broker that message will be first stored in a queue and then the consumer will read that message from the queue which is in a rabbit mq broker. We can
create any number of queues in a rabbit mq broker 
      Once the message is read, it is consumed and removed from the queue, a message can be processed exactly only once

4. Message
     Message is nothing but the information that is sent from producer to the consumer through a rabbit mq, it can be any type like string format or json or byte array or plain text or HTML 

5. Exchange
     Exchange it acts as an intermediary between producer and queue, instead of sending a message directly to the queue, a producer can send those messages directly to the exchange first
and then exchange will basically route those message to the respective queues

6. Routing Key
     Routing key is a key that exchange basically uses to route a message to the respective queues. It is like address for the message. Consider in a complex applications we have to use
a multiple queues in a rabbitmq broker and we have 2queues q1 and q2, so whenever producer sends a
message to the exchange, then exchange basically don't know in which queue the message should be route, in that case we use a routing key to route that message to the particular queue 
    So producer will basically send a message along with the routing key, so that exchange will
use that routing key to route that message to the respective queues 

7. Binding
     Binding is a link between queue and exchange, exchange basically use a routing key to route a
message to the respective queues  and this is nothing but a binding, there should be a binding between exchange and queue then only the exchange can able to route a message to the respective queues 

RabbitMQ Architecture
   In a typical messaging system architecture, we have producer and we have a consumer, in between producer and consumer we have a message broker, so producer will basically send a message to the message broker and consumer will basically read those messages from the message broker 
   In case of rabbit mq messaging system architecture you can see there is a one more component called exchange so producer will basically send a message first to The Exchange and then exchange
will route that message to the queue and then consumer will basically consume or read that message from the queue 
   In case of a complex application we need to create a multiple queues in a rabbit mq broker, so the producer will basically send a message to the Exchange first and then exchange will basically use a routing key to route that message to the respective queues and then consumer will
basically consume or read the message from the respective queues  
   Consider we have multiple queues in a rabbit MQ architecture, for example Q1,Q2,Q3 and whenever producer want to send a message to the Q3 then it will send a message along with the routing key to the exchange and then exchange will basically use that routing key to identify in which queue
the message should be route. Consider we have a routing key 3 then exchange will basically send that message to the Q3 and consider producer want to send a message to the Q1 then  it will pass a
message along with the routing key 1, then exchange will use that routing key and it will route that message to the Q1. So in this way the Binding or link should be established between exchange
and queue by using routing key 

