          Imagine that you have an E-Commerce application and when the user places the order in it, you want notifications to go through the email, inventory update, payment. So if you think that all these things are done synchronously (ie) that the user has to wait for everything
at the same moment when he placed the order (ie) until the email is sent or the inventory update is not done, he is waiting so this would be such a bad experience 
       But this does not happen we do these things asynchronously, in which we get event driven architecture, we get message queues like those things. So when we talk about message queue our most popular message queue is Rabbit MQ 

What is RabbitMQ?
   RabbitMQ is an open source message broker or a message queue which helps different parts of the system to communicate with each other asynchronously, and decouple producers and consumers 
    Suppose we have a post office, so there will be a producer who will keep the letter in the post box (ie) our queue and our letter will be a message, so our post office is Rabbit MQ
which ensure that your letter is delivered and there is some other person which we can call as consumer who will pick it up
    So the main job of Rabbit MQ is, it will receive the messages from the producer will route them to the place where the message has to be delivered and will store it temporarily until it is consumed and will deliver it to the consumers

Why RabbitMQ ?
    Consider we have an appl like Amazon, whenever our order is placed then we have to confirm the order through email (ie) we have to sent a notification that your order confirmed, then we will update the inventory and we will do payment processing and notify delivery service 
    If we do all these things synchronously means in one request then it will be very slow 
and error can also come, instead whenever order is placed our order service will publish the events on Rabbit MQ which is our message queue, then the other services like email, inventory, payment, delivery will consume the message asynchronously and also if any service is down Rabbit MQ will keep that message safe, when our service is up then it will pick 

Benefits
1. Decoupling - our services are not directly depending on each other means there is no tight coupling, all service can work separately 

2. Scalability - If we want to scale up then whatever service we have, we 
can easily add multiple consumers 

3. Reliability - our messages will persist in our MQ, even if our services crash 

4. Asynchronous processing - whatever task or service we are doing we will do it in background so our processing is asynchronous 

5. Load balancing - suppose our appl have a lot of users while placing the order and we have emailservice to pick order message and send email, so now imagine we have 10 consumers where emailservice is running and our message queue from here message has to go to services, so RabbitMQ will ensure that the messages going to consumers should be balanced their load (ie) if we have 10 consumers then all the messages will not go to one consumer or two consumers, it will manage the load evenly so that my consumers can manage the load properly when they consume the message so that all our consumers can be utilized properly 

6. Retry and dead lettering support - If we have delivered the message and for some reason it was not consumed by consumers then we can retry it and send it again
   If our messages are failing then after multiple retries we can put them in dead letter queue


Core components of RabbitMQ 
1. Producer
      It will publish messages to exchange, it doesn't do it directly in queue, it does it in exchange and from exchange it goes to queue

Technical behavior 
1. open the connection and channel from RabbitMQ 
2. publish the message using name of the exchange, routing key  message body, properties like headers means on the basis of headers we have some routing, flag of persistence means if you want our message to persist in queue, if you want to give priority that we have to send this message first 
    Every message our producer will send, it will reach our exchange in binary form and after exchange when it goes to queue it remains in binary form
    So whatever client libraries your service is written, it can be javascript, python,java etc
it will transmits the message in binary because our rabbitmq works on amqp protocol
which is our binary protocol,  so the messages which we send are transmitted in binary form. In case if my message is in json then it is the responsibility of the developer to serialize the data in bytes before sending

2. Exchange
     Our exchange is the brain of rabbitmq routing system, it decides how messages flow from producers to one or more queues 
    When a message arrives from producer, the exchange look at its type and the bindings and decide which queue should receive the message 

Responsiblities
1. Receive messages from producer
2. Match routing keys against bindings
3. Route the messages into the correct queue

Exchange type 
1. Direct exchange - Exact routing key match - which will match directly with our routing key. If we have logs or we have to do routing in any target base in that case we use this
2. Fanout exchange - Broadcast to all queues bound - suppose we have multiple queues and we need to send to all queues. This is used in notifications and broadcast system it is used there ok now 
3. Topic exchange - Pattern based routing (ie) uses wildcard patterns (*), suppose we have multiple service like user.created, order.created so now if we want to route the message to those services we can use *.created 
4. Headers - Route based on headers - advanced filtering


3. Queue 
      It is a message buffer. It is a storage unit that holds message until they are consumed, by default this is like FIFO means first in first out, the message that came first will go first
      Messages stay in the queue until
1. A consumer retrieves and acknowledge it
2. The message expires (TTL) time to live, then the message will not expire 
3. If our queue is deleted

Key Properties
1. durable=true -  if our broker, i.e. RabbitMQ is restarted, then also our queue will not be deleted, it will survive
2. exclusive=false,  it will be used through the same connection which has created it, 
3. autodelete=false, suppose if my queue does not have any consumer, then it will be deleted by itself
4. TTL, if we give TTL in the messages means message expired time, then our message will expire
5. DLX(dead letter exchange), DLX used for failed messages 
6. lazy mode - our queue stores the messages in RAM but if we give lazy mode, then it will store in disk 

Responsibility 
1. Hold the message safely, until it is processed
2. Manage the order of the message and deliver the order
3. support the reliability means it takes an acknowledgement from the consumer and it persists the message, dead letter queue for our failed messages
4. supports scaling, means if our message is of one type, and there are multiple consumers, then it can deal with them, so our scale up is done


Queue behavior based on arguments 
1.Standard Queue (default queue) 
    - most common type of queue, in which we have first in first out, except if we are using priority
    - our messages can be stored in our memory or disk, depending on the   
    - can have multiple consumers and they also do load balancing, 

use case
1. General background jobs, that we have put a message our work will continue in the background, like notification
2. In microservices

2. Priority Queue
     - Messages can have priority level, an integer value 
     - Higher priority messages are delivered first, even if others arrived earlier

use case 
- Payment alerts, urgent notification,critical updates

3. Dead Letter Queue
      - It stores failed messages which we could not process successfully, we may think that we can retry the messages, if the message fails

Why dead letter queue? 
     Consider there is some problem in payload, because of which the message is failing again and again means it is retrying, sending to the consumer, but still it is failing, in that case we don't want that infinite loop (ie) msg is failing, and then again it is retrying. So after a limit, we want to put that failed message in dead letter queue and we debug it

use case, 
- error handling, retries, message auditing

4. Lazy Queue
     - Store messages on disk immediately instead of memory. 
     - Reduces RAM usage when message volume is high
     - Slightly slower but very memory efficient

use case
- Large queues, background workloads, high backlog systems

5. Time To Live(TTL) queue
      Messages automatically expire after a certain time

use case
- Temporary notification, caching, expiring tasks

6. Single Active Consumer Queue
       If we have multiple consumers then at one time only one consumer is active, and when it is disconnected then it will take over the next consumer, so if we want our message to be processed in sequence then it will be used

use case
- Task is to be done on a strict order

7. Stream Queue - For event processing

4. Binding
     Binding is basically connection between the exchange and the queue. When the message comes from the producer to the exchange, then from the exchange to the binding, it connects to the queue. So basically it defines which message goes into which queue based on routing keys, headers. If bindings are not there, then our exchange can't route the message, they will just drop messages
     One exchange bound to many queues. One queue bound to many messages.


5. Consumer
     Consumer is our application or service, which reads the message from queue and processes it. It will connect with RabbitMQ, it will subscribe to queue and  waits for new message to come

Consumers can:
1. It can auto acknowledge messages 
2. It can also manually acknowledge after processing
3  It can also send negative ACK, it can send to requeue or send to dead letter queue 

Responsibilities
1. It retrieves the message from queue and processes it 
2. sends ACK and NACK
3. It can be retry, or it can go to dead letter queue
4. scale horizontally for parallel processing (ie) emailservice has one consumer and it is not able to handle the load since lot of messages coming to emailservice, then we can
scale horizontally (ie) we put multiple worker nodes, so that it can work in parallel

6.  Channel
      It is lightweight virtual connection inside a TCP connection, we can have multiple channels per connection. Used for publishing, consuming messages and to manage queues

why?
- opening and closing it is expensive but channels are cheap
for example if you have an application, we have one TCP connection in this system, but for producers and consumers in one connection we can use multiple channels

7. Connection
      A real TCP connection between your app and RabbitMQ broker, which is established with the help of our AMQP protocol


