Explanation


1) JSON payloads (Jackson converter) + DTO classes
✅ What problem this solves
By default, RabbitMQ messages are bytes. Without a converter, you end up manually serializing/deserializing JSON strings.
With a Jackson message converter, Spring automatically:
a. Converts Java DTO → JSON when publishing
b. Converts JSON → Java DTO when consuming (in @RabbitListener)

✅ What in the code does this?
A) DTOs (records)

Example:
public record OrderEvent(String orderId, String eventType, String description, Instant createdAt) {}

Meaning: this is the message payload (structured data).
Spring will serialize it to JSON when you publish, and reconstruct it back when you consume.

B) RabbitCommonConfig.jacksonMessageConverter()

@Bean
public MessageConverter jacksonMessageConverter(ObjectMapper objectMapper) {
  return new Jackson2JsonMessageConverter(objectMapper);
}

Meaning: you register a MessageConverter bean.

Why this matters in Spring Boot: the Spring Boot reference says that when a MessageConverter bean is defined, it is associated automatically with the auto-configured messaging template.

So, this single bean makes your RabbitTemplate.convertAndSend() send JSON automatically and your @RabbitListener methods receive DTOs automatically.

C) Using DTOs in publisher and listener
Publisher:
  rabbitTemplate.convertAndSend(exchange, routingKey, event, correlationData);

Listener:
  @RabbitListener(queues = "q.order.created")
  public void onMessage(OrderEvent event) { ... }

Meaning: The converter is applied on both sides.

2) DLQ + Retry + TTL (how it works in your code)
There are two ways a message can end up in DLQ:
✅ A) Message expires (TTL)
If a message sits too long in queue, TTL triggers → message is dead-lettered.
✅ B) Message fails processing
Consumer throws exception → Spring retries → if still failing, message is rejected → dead-lettered.

2.1 DLQ setup in code (Queue arguments)
In DirectExchangeConfig, you did:

QueueBuilder.durable(Q_CREATED)
  .withArgument("x-dead-letter-exchange", DLX)
  .withArgument("x-dead-letter-routing-key", RK_CREATED_DLQ)
  .withArgument("x-message-ttl", TTL_MS)
  .build();

Meaning of each:

x-dead-letter-exchange: where RabbitMQ should re-publish failed/expired messages
x-dead-letter-routing-key: routing key RabbitMQ uses when sending to DLX
x-message-ttl: if message stays longer than TTL in queue → expire → send to DLX

Then you created DLQ queue and bound it:
BindingBuilder.bind(createdDlq).to(deadLetterExchange).with(RK_CREATED_DLQ);

So the pipeline becomes:
Main Queue → (fail/expire) → DLX → DLQ Queue

2.2 Retry (Listener retry) — what triggers it
In application.yml you set:

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.retry.enabled: true
spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.retry.max-attempts: 3
...

Spring Boot explicitly lists these listener.simple.retry.* properties, including max attempts and intervals. 

So what happens at runtime:
1. Consumer receives message
2. Consumer throws exception (RuntimeException)
3. Spring retries the listener according to those properties
4. After max attempts, Spring rejects message (and because default-requeue-rejected=false, it won’t requeue)

This default-requeue-rejected property is also listed in Spring Boot’s rabbit properties table.

2.3 Why you set default-requeue-rejected: false

spring.rabbitmq.listener.simple.default-requeue-rejected: false

Meaning: If after retries the message is still failing, it should be rejected (not put back again into the same queue).
If it were true, you can get an infinite loop: fail → requeue → fail → requeue…
So false is the recommended approach when you use DLQ.

2.4 How you purposely triggered failure (for DLQ demo)
In listener:

if (event.description().contains("fail")) {
  throw new RuntimeException("Simulated failure");
}

So you can test DLQ easily by publishing an event with "fail" in description.

2.5 Template retry vs listener retry (important distinction)
Your application.yml also enables:
   spring.rabbitmq.template.retry.enabled: true

Spring Boot explicitly documents this property and gives an example enabling retry on AmqpTemplate (publisher side).

So:
template retry = retry publishing if connection issues happen
listener retry = retry consuming if processing fails

They solve different reliability problems.

3) Publisher confirms + mandatory returns (what they mean)
This is about publisher reliability.
✅ 3.1 Publisher confirms (ACK/NACK from broker)

You enabled:
spring.rabbitmq.publisher-confirm-type: correlated

Spring Boot reference lists spring.rabbitmq.publisher-confirm-type. 

Meaning: RabbitMQ will acknowledge whether it accepted the message into the broker.
ACK: broker received message
NACK: broker rejected message (rare but possible)

In code you handle confirms:
template.setConfirmCallback((correlationData, ack, cause) -> {...});

And you create correlation id:
new CorrelationData(UUID.randomUUID().toString())


Meaning: correlation id helps match “this confirm belongs to that publish”.

✅ 3.2 Mandatory flag + returns (message could not be routed)
You enabled:
spring.rabbitmq.publisher-returns: true
spring.rabbitmq.template.mandatory: true

Spring Boot explicitly lists publisher-returns and template.mandatory. 

Meaning:

If a message is published to an exchange but no queue binding matches the routing key, then RabbitMQ can either:

silently drop it (bad)
or return it back to publisher (good)

With mandatory=true + returns enabled, RabbitMQ will return unroutable messages back to the publisher, and you handle them using:

template.setReturnsCallback(returned -> {...});

✅ 3.3 Why you added /direct/unroutable
You publish with routing key "order.unknown" that has no binding:

rabbitTemplate.convertAndSend(EXCHANGE, "order.unknown", event, cd);

So:
1. RabbitMQ accepts message → confirm ACK
2. But message can’t be routed → returns callback fires

