D. Retry & Backoff Strategies
What problem it solves
    What if a consumer fails temporarily?

Examples:
1. Database down
2. External API timeout
3. Network glitch

Retry strategies
Strategy 1: TTL‑based Retry Queue (most common)

Main Queue
  ↓ fail
Retry Queue (TTL = 10s)
  ↓
Main Queue

Spring Boot queue config

QueueBuilder.durable("order.retry")
  .withArgument("x-message-ttl", 10000)
  .withArgument("x-dead-letter-exchange", "")
  .withArgument("x-dead-letter-routing-key", "order.main")
  .build();

✅ Broker‑controlled
✅ Predictable
✅ Production standard

Strategy 2: Multiple retry queues (exponential backoff)
Retry‑1 (10s) → Retry‑2 (30s) → Retry‑3 (1m) → DLQ

Used by:
Payment gateways
Event pipelines


Strategy 3: Spring RetryInterceptor
✅ Simple
❌ No delay
✅ CPU‑based retry

E. Idempotent Consumers
What problem it solves
   “What if the same message is delivered more than once?”

Messaging systems guarantee:
At‑least‑once delivery

So duplicates will happen.

Example failure scenario
Consumer processes message
DB commit succeeds
ACK fails
Message redelivered

Idempotency pattern
Step 1: Unique message ID
    eventId = UUID 
Step 2: Store processed IDs
    processed_events(event_id) 
Step 3: Check before processing
 if (repository.existsByEventId(event.getId())) {    
        return; // ignore duplicate
 }
 process(event);
 repository.save(event.getId());

